postcontent: This is a brand new in box CMMG M4 AR-15 semi-automatic rifle chambered for 5.56mm NATO. This rifle features a 16" 4140 Chrome Moly Steel M4 profile barrel with a 1:9" twist rate suitable for most commerical ammunition. This barrel boasts CMMG's W.A.S.P. salt bath nitrocarbuerization treatment, sometimes known as nitriding, which offers improved wear, abrasion, and corrosion resistance as compared to chrome lining or phosphating. Unlike chrome lining, where the chrome is built up on the surface, nitriding converts the surface without build-up, so accuracy is not compromised. The barrel and upper receiver have M4 feed ramps for flawless cycling. A "F" marked front sight post/gas block is fitted, and a removable MBUS rear sight is included. The upper receiver is forged aluminum with a flat top Picatinny rail for easy and secure mounting of optics. This particular rifle has a quad rail handguard installed, making mounting accessories like tactical lights, fore grips, and bipods, among others, quick and easy. The lower is forged as well, with a low shelf for RDIAS, and is compatible with standard mil-spec componentry. The magazine well is bevelled for quicker, more confident reloads. An adjustable butt stock and A2-style pistol grip are outfitted. Front and rear sling mounts are mounted for easy carrying. One 30 round PMAG is included. title: For Sale:  Rare, Customized, Centennial Edition 94 AE
postcontent:
Why is it rare? 
Most customized lever actions are Marlin or Henry, this is a customized, centennial edition of the Winchester 94 AE in 30-30.
So it's rare for being a customized Winchester and rare as it's an "1894-1994" centennial edition (as can be seen in the pictures. )

The customized features are:
Polymer furniture. 
Trigger has been worked on
Loop enlarged (not much, it looks to have been heated and expanded)
Sights moved to end of the gun, so even though it's a carbine the sights are much more accurate as they are as far apart as they can be on this rifle. 
The sight is a peep sight. 
Ceramic coating to inhibit rust and corrosion. 
Leather butt cuff for holding 5 rounds of .30-.30
Nylon sling. 

I bought it off a consignment rack so I'm not sure what else has been customized, they do a lot of internal stuff. 

I don't think the guy was happy about having to sell it so he gave it to the gun store and didn't really want to talk about it. 

I was told it was customized by Yost Bonitz when I bought it, but they contacted a few days later to say it had been done by someone who used to work for Yost Bonitz, so I don't know who did the work, but he did a great job. 

It had never been loaded when I bought it, much less fired. 

I've put 40 rounds through it, 20 were Hornady LeveRevolution, 20 were normal Hornady rounds. 
It's in very good condition. 
I'll include what 30-30 ammo I have, maybe 20-40 rounds, I haven't checked lately.

title: For Sale:  H&R Survivor .45Colt/.410
postcontent:
H&R Survivor model in 45 Colt and .410. This is pretty much the same break open, single shot shotgun that we all know but with a rifled barrel for .45 Colt and a removable choke for shooting .410 loads. This also differs from the typical H&R with it's pistol grip/thumb-hole stock. The but of the stock is hollow with a removable base for storing things such as a survival kit, extra ammunition, etc.

As stated earlier the barrel is rifled, so shooting .45 Colt loads is reasonably accurate. When it comes to shooting .410 loads, there is a choke that screws into the barrel to minimize the erratic spread of lead shot caused by the rifling. There is a key included to unscrew the choke. The choke must be removed when shooting .45 Colt. Like other .45/.410 firearms you cannot fire .410 slugs as they are of a smaller diameter than the barrel.

I've put less than 50 rounds through this total. About 25 .45 rounds at paper and <25 .410 target loads at clay pigeons, which did surprisingly well. I wouldn't go shoot skeet competition with it, but it held it's own....

Asking $250 FTF in Lycoming County. Not looking for any trades at the moment, just cash. Thanks for looking.

title: For Sale:  Two WW2 pistols
postcontent:
I have two WW2 pistols for sale-

First pistol is a p38 walther 9mm. My grandfather brought this back from the European theater. The story is he was on a patrol and came across a germen officer ridding a horse. My grandfathers patrol stopped him and he took the pistol. Its been sitting in a old trunk ever since. All numbers match and is in good shape. Based on the serial number it was made late in the war. It still shoots well and come with extra mags. The barrel is bright and has good riffling with minor pitting on the outside.  Very nice piece of history that you can still shoot.

Second pistol is a p08 luger 9mm. This is a ww2 Russian capture. All numbers match and was produced in 41. This is also a shooter and is in good shape. The wood grips are original to the gun. The barrel also has minor pitting but has good riffling. I have the original holster for this gun with extra mags. 

Im want $2000 for both guns. I will through in a few boxes of 9mm ammo and a extra ww2 holster. I will separate if need be for $1000 each but the ammo and extra holster will be more. The price is firm in cash or money order and will not take trades or payment plans. You must have a current NC pistol permit for both guns. If you email me junk or low ball offers I will not respond. If you have any questions feel free to email me. Thanks for looking.
